  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation sequence turns
a phi-of-geps into a phi-of-offsets feeding a single GEP with inbounds nuw flags.
In the source, only one incoming GEP was inbounds, while the other was not. By
cloning one incoming GEP (the inbounds one) and hoisting it out of the phi,
InstCombine incorrectly preserved the inbounds (and nuw) flags on a GEP whose
index is a phi that includes a non-inbounds path. This strengthens poison
conditions: inbounds GEP from null is poison, whereas the original had a
non-inbounds path that produced a defined result. Alive2 reports \"Target is more
poisonous than source\" with %p = null and %c = false.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\nThe log shows:\n- %gep1 is canonicalized to getelementptr inbounds nuw i8,
ptr %p, i64 4.\n- %gep2 is canonicalized to getelementptr i8, ptr %p, i64 8 (no
inbounds).\n- The foldGEPOfPhi rewrites the phi of pointers into %1 = phi i64 [4,
%if], [8, %else] and then %2 = getelementptr inbounds nuw i8, ptr %p, i64 %1,
preserving both inbounds and nuw from %gep1. This is the first transformation
that changes semantics.\n- Alive2 demonstrates that the target produces poison
while source is not.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe culprit is foldGEPOfPhi
(called from visitGetElementPtrInst). It clones one of the incoming GEPs (Op1)
down into the use-site and, when the GEPs differ at one index, replaces the
differing operand with a new PHI. However, it blindly preserves the flags
(inbounds and no-wrap) from Op1 on the new GEP, even though the other incoming
GEP(s) may not have those flags. Inbounds and NUW/NSW are path-sensitive;
applying them to a merged operation with a PHI index is only valid if all
incoming GEPs have those flags. Failing to intersect/strip flags strengthens
assumptions and introduces poison.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nModify
foldGEPOfPhi to intersect flags across all incoming GEPs and drop any flag that
is not present on all inputs. Specifically:\n- Compute AllInBounds, AllNUW,
AllNSW by AND'ing the corresponding flags of each incoming GEPOperator feeding
the PHI.\n- After cloning Op1 to NewGEP (and possibly substituting the differing
index with a PHI), clear flags on NewGEP that are not universally true across all
inputs.\n\nEdit at llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp lines
2849-2873:\n\nReplace the tail of foldGEPOfPhi to:\n\n  // Track flags across
incoming GEPs feeding the PHI.\n  bool AllInBounds =
cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->isInBounds();\n  bool AllNUW =
cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->hasNoUnsignedWrap();\n  bool AllNSW =
cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->hasNoSignedWrap();\n\n  for (auto I =
PN->op_begin() + 1, E = PN->op_end(); I != E; ++I) {\n    auto *OpG =
dyn_cast<GEPOperator>(*I);\n    if (!OpG)\n      return nullptr; // Should not
happen given previous checks.\n    AllInBounds &= OpG->isInBounds();\n    AllNUW
&= OpG->hasNoUnsignedWrap();\n    AllNSW &= OpG->hasNoSignedWrap();\n  }\n\n
auto *NewGEP = cast<GetElementPtrInst>(Op1->clone());\n  if (DI == -1) {\n    //
All the GEPs feeding the PHI are identical. Clone one down into our\n    // BB so
that it can be merged with the current GEP.\n  } else {\n    // All the GEPs
feeding the PHI differ at a single offset. Clone a GEP\n    // into the current
block so it can be merged, and create a new PHI to\n    // set that index.\n
PHINode *NewPN;\n    {\n      IRBuilderBase::InsertPointGuard Guard(Builder);\n
Builder.SetInsertPoint(PN);\n      NewPN =
Builder.CreatePHI(Op1->getOperand(DI)->getType(),\n
PN->getNumOperands());\n    }\n\n    for (auto &I : PN->operands())\n
NewPN->addIncoming(cast<GEPOperator>(I)->getOperand(DI),\n
PN->getIncomingBlock(I));\n\n    NewGEP->setOperand(DI, NewPN);\n  }\n\n  //
Intersect flags: only preserve flags that hold for all incoming GEPs.\n  if
(!AllInBounds)\n    NewGEP->setIsInBounds(false);\n  if (!AllNUW)\n
NewGEP->setHasNoUnsignedWrap(false);\n  if (!AllNSW)\n
NewGEP->setHasNoSignedWrap(false);\n\n  NewGEP->insertBefore(*GEP.getParent(),
GEP.getParent()->getFirstInsertionPt());\n  return NewGEP;\n\nNotes:\n-
GEPOperator exposes isInBounds(), hasNoUnsignedWrap(), hasNoSignedWrap();
GetElementPtrInst exposes setters setIsInBounds(bool),
setHasNoUnsignedWrap(bool), setHasNoSignedWrap(bool).\n- This keeps flags only
when they are valid along all incoming paths, preventing unintended poison.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nBy intersecting (rather than blindly copying) inbounds and no-wrap
flags when folding a GEP over a PHI of GEPs, we avoid strengthening assumptions
in the presence of mixed-flag inputs. This fix ensures the transformed IR
preserves semantics: the resulting GEP will not be inbounds/NUW unless all
incoming GEPs are, and Alive2's reported miscompilation disappears. This change
affects only foldGEPOfPhi and is consistent with LLVM\u2019s requirement to
conservatively preserve flags through IR transformations.",
